SIMPLE: evolve
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Evolve
<hw>E*volve"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Evolved</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Evolving</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>evolvere</ets>,
<ets>evolutum</ets>; <ets>e</ets> out + <ets>volvere</ets> to roll. See
<er>Voluble</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To unfold or unroll; to open
and expand; to disentangle and exhibit clearly and satisfactorily; to
develop; to derive; to educe.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The animal soul sooner <qex>evolves</qex> itself to its full orb
and extent than the human soul.</q> <rj><qau>Sir. M.
Hale.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The principles which art involves, science alone
<qex>evolves</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Whewell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Not by any power evolved from man's own resources, but by a power
which descended from above.</q> <rj><qau>J. C. Shairp.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To throw out; to emit; <as>as, to <ex>evolve</ex>
odors</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Evolve</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Evolve
<hw>E*volve"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become open, disclosed, or
developed; to pass through a process of evolution.</def>
<rj><au>Prior.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Evolvement</ent>⟦br⟧
